'''Djahi''', '''Djahy''' or '''Tjahi''' was the [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] designation for southern [[Retenu]].<ref>Gardiner, Alan. ''Egypt of the Pharaohs.'' Oxford University Press, 1961., p.285.</ref> It ran from approximately [[Ashkelon]] to [[History of ancient Lebanon|Lebanon]] and inland as far as [[Galilee]].<ref>Steindorff, George. ''When Egypt Ruled the East.'' p. 47. University of Chicago Press, 1942.</ref> It was described as the [[drainage basin]] of the [[Jordan River]] during the [[Battle of Kadesh|battles with Kadesh]] of the [[Eighteenth dynasty of Egypt|Eighteenth]] and [[Nineteenth dynasty of Egypt|Nineteenth dynasties of Egypt]].

It was the scene of the [[Battle of Djahy]] between Rameses III and the Sea Peoples.

